TY  - JOUR
AU  - Li, Lei
AU  - Li, Yi
AU  - Macchiavelli, Marco
AU  - Zhou, Xing (Alex)
T1  - Liquidity Restrictions, Runs, and Central Bank Interventions: Evidence from Money Market Funds
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhab065
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 11
SP  - 5402
EP  - 5437
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Liquidity restrictions on investors, like the redemption gates and liquidity fees introduced in the 2016 money market fund (MMF) reform, are meant to improve financial stability. However, we find evidence that such liquidity restrictions exacerbated the run on prime MMFs during the COVID-19 crisis. Our results indicate that gates and fees could generate strategic complementarities among investors in crisis times. Severe outflows from prime MMFs led the Federal Reserve to intervene with the Money Market Mutual Fund Liquidity Facility (MMLF). Using MMLF microdata, we show how the provision of “liquidity of last resort” stabilized prime funds.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhab065
ER  - 



